#, fuzzy, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring Dynamic IPv6 Address"
msgstr ""
"配置动态IPv6地址\n"
"\n"
"== Introduction\n"
"\n"
"IPv6 addressing allows for the allocation of dynamic addresses. This means that devices on an IPv6 network can automatically obtain an IP address without the need for manual configuration. This can simplify the process of setting up and maintaining a network.\n"
"\n"
"== Types of Dynamic IPv6 Address Configuration\n"
"\n"
"There are two main methods for configuring dynamic IPv6 addresses: stateless address autoconfiguration (SLAAC) and dynamic host configuration protocol version 6 (DHCPv6).\n"
"\n"
"=== Stateless Address Autoconfiguration (SLAAC)\n"
"\n"
"SLAAC is a method where devices on the network derive their IPv6 addresses using information provided by routers on the network. The router advertises the IPv6 prefix and the network interface identifier (NII). Devices then combine these to form a unique IP address.\n"
"\n"
"=== Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol version 6 (DHCPv6)\n"
"\n"
"DHCPv6 is a client-server protocol that allows a DHCP server to automatically assign IPv6 addresses and other configuration parameters to clients on the network. Clients send DHCPv6 requests to solicit an address and the server responds with the assigned address.\n"
"\n"
"== Configuring Dynamic IPv6 Address on a Router or Switch\n"
"\n"
"To configure dynamic IPv6 address on a router or switch, you need to enable either SLAAC or DHCPv6 on the device. This can usually be done through the device's command line interface (CLI) or web-based management interface. Once enabled, the device will handle the automatic assignment of IPv6 addresses to devices on the network.\n"
"\n"
"== Conclusion\n"
"\n"
"Dynamic IPv6 addressing provides a convenient way to allocate IP addresses on a network without manual configuration. By enabling SLAAC or DHCPv6, devices can automatically obtain IPv6 addresses, making network setup and maintenance easier."

